<br>
1) The person deciding the loot is fair<br>
2) The people on the raid spend a lot of time together<br>
3) Loot whores are either non-existant or kept in check<br>
<br>
You seem to be saying that #1 was the problem (although since you complained and left, the other people on the raid might say it was #3, but I don't know you, so I won't pass any judgement here).  Deciding loot fairly is not easy, and many raid leaders have a bumpy road learning how to do it.  Eventually, if you are a good raid leader, you get so many good decisions under your belt that people stop complaining about the bad ones.<br>
<br>
The primary question that most merit raid leaders use to decide loot is &quot;Who has gone the longest without getting anything?&quot;  Just because you have gone on the most raids doesn't mean that all loot goes to you.  If you got something on the last raid, you have just as much merit as the new guy who is on his first (more or less).  Most raid leaders do give special consideration for people who only need 1 more piece to complete their armor set, or any other special circumstance that might merit loot.<br>
<br>
